column1: How many confirmed cases of COVID-19 in the US will be reported for the week ending 5 June﻿ 2021?

column6: ['Technology', 'Society', 'Health']
There doesn't seem to be a viable route to >150K
Late on adjusting this forecast- < 150K seems overwhelmingly likely.

I was worried about the recent uptick in cases, but I don't think that even if that uptick continues that cases will exceed 150k for the forecast week, especially given likely lower testing/reporting around the Memorial Day holiday.
Case decreases are usually sharper than reductions in deaths, but they do plateau once in a while. While it seems likely that cases will dip below 150K, I don't think it's overwhelmingly likely yet.

The recent uptick in cases over the past couple days may be just noisy data, or it may represent the start of an uptick in cases, perhaps due to fewer people wearing masks indoors and the spread of variants. I'll park at the crowd forecast until the trend become clear over the next few days.
I think it will be very close... Est. 136,000-148,000
Risks with more contagious Indian variant and Memorial day and still % unvaccinated.
Downward trend continues and is now at 24k per day. Threshold for 150k is 21.4k per day. We have a week to go Could be close to the 150k threshold.
current trends continue but possibility of a new wave or dramtic slowdown in infection rates always possible

7day average of cases/day has been declining along a nearly perfect line for almost 40 days now. I don't see that changing in the next 13 days. There will likely be between 52k and 56k cases that week (53.9k currently projected). We will probably be under 150k/week with May 26 data. I should have gone to 100% sooner.

Threshold for 150k is 21.4K per day Current rate is 31k day and decreasing 2 weeks until measurement week. Rate has dropped by 5-7k in last couple of weeks, so could get to below 150k but this relying on rates continuing to drop fast.
The decline in cases isn't slowing down, which is great!

The question is really how fast can we get to ~ 20k/day. Of course, vaccination rate is the key, but how rapidly are we normalizing is also important. Traffic, in many instances, seems to be back to ~ 90% of pre-covid levels. This normalization rate applies brakes to case reduction at the margins and if we compare US curve vs say UK curve, it seems that US cases may be slightly more sticky. Currently, US is tracking ~ 218K/week, so I would have to weight the 150-250 slightly more.

Update. The 7-day average of cases/day may finally be starting to slow down, and it looks like it might land at around 30k/day, pushing cases for the forecast week to the ballpark of 200k. But it still could end up lower than 150k.
The slope may be leveling off or it may be just a temporary effect.
If it stays on its current rate of decline, it will definitely go under 150K. Leaving some room for upswings or plateaus.
Still on the same forecast of 132-170k, but it’s looking nearer to the lower end now with the linear trend maintained longer than expected.
Going 50:50 now between < and > 150k. If cases keep on declining at the actual rate (-2.5%/d), the number will be ~140k.
7 day average of seven day change = 86.64% 86.64% ^ (1/7) = 97.97% daily change 26 days left: 97.97% ^26 = 58.7% Confirmed cases for week until May 10: 271 099 271 099 * 58.7% = 159 151
Holding steady with slow movement down around 40k per day, which would give 280k for the week Threshold for 250k is 35k per day. We are heading in that direction with 2 to 3 weeks to go

In all but a handful of states I think cases will continue to drop steadily for 2-3 weeks. Of the remaining, where cases start to rise, the effect should only slow the rate of decline we are seeing for the US as a whole. Steady rolling out of vaccinations should also mitigate some of the uptick in cases due to easing of imposed restrictions through late May. Overall at this point I think it will be quite close to the break point at 150K Forecasting range 132-170K

This is really a bet that cases will probably stop declining linearly and will start leveling off somewhere above 20k/day average for the forecast period. Is this the right way to think about it? I'm not sure cases won't continue to decline further than most of us are thinking in the forecast period.

A linear forecast based on the decline from April 14 to May 4 predicts 35.5k cases for the week ending June 5. But it seems very unlikely to be that low. And whatever happens, it almost certainly won't be linear on the time scale of this forecast. Currently, we're at 336k cases/week (7-day moving average), and cases/day have fallen 33% in the past 3 weeks. I certainly don't think it's likely to go higher than that; Rt = ~0.9 right now. I'm going to guess we'll be at ~25k to 29k cases/day for that week, plus or minus a few thousand.
Threshold 150k = 21.5k per day 250k = 35.7 per day 350k = 50k per day

I think a continued drop seems most likely due to vaccination rates. The ensemble model agrees with that too, showing 249k weekly cases 4 weeks from now with a 95% confidence interval of 114k to 470k. Israel seems like a good example of what can happen when you get to high vaccination rates and we're approaching that point.
